yeah, i was able to get clients to 
send GameMessages over the network
by simply specifing the recipeint and message type 
in the msg the client want's to send. This is horrible
as this is supposed to be taken care of at the 
api boundary, not ux concern. BUT, it's good enough 
for now, infact, it's slightly convincing me to use 
packet framing, as i think it allows for more dynamic 
cases, although more teidous, as compared  to using
json. Or maybe this might be an oppurtunity to fully 
explore protobufs? I'll see what it can do

But atm, I want the client to include their ssids for 
the game, so the srver can reference their play session
I think that's easier. So now, the server just appends
the ssid into the NewGameMessage content, using ';'
as a delimeter, and ssid as the 'key' if you may.
So the client sees something like this:
	 ```
	 Message {
			 MessageType: NewGameMessage,
			 From: secretServerId,
			 Dest: your-future-uuid,
			 Content: "Game starting;ssid928018u0=j23",
	 }
	 ```

	 And the server
	 ```
	 Messagee {
			 From: you,
			 Dest: away,
			 Content: "your-play;ssid",
			 MessageType: GameMessage
	 }
	 ```

Violation of these rules will automatically declare
the other player winner, easier that way atm

And slowly, we can see how Protobufs, or binary framing look 
more like the appealing solution, otherswise, we'd need 
excessive tracking and almost sentience for our app to 
know when to switch btwn normal message or game message

